<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-adding-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Adding Vectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_4zedkel9">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_2gtbf6s8">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1m1mby0m">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5q0354ii">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_5yx9npb0">
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <p xml:id="auto_wnjmcy3v">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_9cm1q15h">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_78tdfyw4">Add vectors graphically and algebraically to find resultant displacement in different situations</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <li xml:id="auto_9jhjvzhb" component="lesson-plan">Grade Level: 10</li>
        <li xml:id="auto_8x5l9ugu" component="lesson-plan">Estimated Duration: 40 minutes</li>
        <p xml:id="auto_txhs4x6o" component="lesson-plan">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_96yrdboj">
                    <title>Know</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ytbpbpjf">The concept of resultant displacement and the tip-to-tail method of vector addition</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_63af72ca">
                    <title>Do</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_brpfbunc">Add vectors graphically using the tip-to-tail method and algebraically using component addition</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ifcz5kq1">
                    <title>Apply</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_5czzhh4b">Use vector addition to find total displacement in multi-step journeys and express vectors in terms of given vectors</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_lc0mor36">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/adding-vectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_r567hp92">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_adding-vectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_2rqcikkn">
            <alert>Anchor Activity: Discovering Vector Addition Through Sequential Displacements</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pgu7yu8o">
            Organise students into groups of 2–3. Distribute graph paper, rulers, and pencils. Guide students through the activity below.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wtgc6iwl">
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_glbayl0n">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_vyurqpo0"><p xml:id="auto_b3y27npz">Guide students to draw clear axes with labelled scales.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bbtmopqf"><p xml:id="auto_dfrrqewm">Help students draw vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> as an arrow from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,2)</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f0t1gy2q"><p xml:id="auto_nmj59f1x">Ensure vector <m>\mathbf{BC}</m> starts where <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> ends (tip-to-tail).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tavg1cac"><p xml:id="auto_j0q7g4m3">Ask probing questions: <q>What is the total horizontal movement from <m>A</m> to <m>C</m>? What is the total vertical movement?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_e0jw7jbv"><p xml:id="auto_bi4fycrf">Guide students to recognise: Horizontal = 5 units, Vertical = 2 units, so <m>\overrightarrow{AC} = \binom{5}{2}</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gzz7icz7"><p xml:id="auto_yuck2v6y">Help students see that <m>\overrightarrow{AC} = \overrightarrow{AB} + \overrightarrow{BC}</m> by adding components.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_s9sl1gd6"><p xml:id="auto_gxqw3l3v">Use student observations as a bridge to formal vector addition rules.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vlu8j0op">
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o78a8z50">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_ics5h4py"><p xml:id="auto_oigxokl7">What is the total horizontal displacement from <m>A</m> to <m>C</m>?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nb386tm4"><p xml:id="auto_wr0vpqeu">What is the total vertical displacement from <m>A</m> to <m>C</m>?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_p7o923ki"><p xml:id="auto_6jcy2ygk">How does the resultant vector <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m> relate to <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m>?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_co9ikdev"><p xml:id="auto_sc7f0u6z">What happens when you add the <m>x</m>-components and <m>y</m>-components separately?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <activity xml:id="auto_zzalcyw3">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_689b6lkf">
            
            <p xml:id="auto_kdc958v8">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_pnej1gvr">
                <alert>What you require:</alert> Graph paper,ruler
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_gdh1zycc">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_b389x6am">
                    Draw the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axis on the graph paper.
                </p>
            </statement> 
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_zqhekidw">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_180f67o4">
                    Draw vector <m>\textbf{AB}</m> from point <m>A(0,0)</m> to point <m>B(2,2)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_bzqjziy1">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qgioahqc">
                    Draw vector <m>\textbf{BC}</m> from point <m>B(2,2)</m> to point <m>C(5,2)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_fht0fxjn">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_84j41apz">
                    Count the number of units moved horizontally (along the <m>x</m> axis) from the starting point <m>A</m> to the final point <m>C</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_nglx9uwm">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0i7ioamq">
                    Similarly, count the number of units moved vertically (along the <m>y</m> axis) from point <m>A</m> to point <m>C</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_89t6e7tk">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6h5xy7mt">
                    Write the resultant displacement in coordinate form <m>\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}</m>, where <m>x</m> represents displacement
                     along the <m>x</m> axis and <m>y</m> represents displacement along the <m>y</m> axis.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_kgf2tsem">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_kda8yq8b">
                    Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <!-- <p xml:id="auto_s309ms7x">
        Consider a displacement between point <m>\mathbf{P}</m> and point <m>\mathbf{N}</m>
        followed a displacement from <m>\mathbf{N}</m> to <m>\mathbf{Q}</m>. 
        The resulting displacement <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m> is written as <m>\mathbf{PQ} = \mathbf{PN} + \mathbf{NQ} </m>
    </p> -->
    <insight xml:id="auto_i0ryv94u">
        <p xml:id="auto_983gg18h">
            Consider a displacement from point <m>P</m> to point <m>Q</m>, followed by another displacement 
            from point <m>Q</m> to point <m>N</m>. The total resultant displacement from <m>P</m> to <m>N</m> is 
            obtained by adding the two vectors sequentially.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_q5jd1pjt">
            This can be expressed as:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_yyyuggpm">
            <md>
                <mrow> \mathbf{PN} \amp = \mathbf{PQ} + \mathbf{QN} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e7eqg3vd">
            where:
            <ol xml:id="auto_5qkys0zk">
                <li xml:id="auto_vfeft17c">
                    <p xml:id="auto_gb952rel">
                        <m>\mathbf{PQ} = \mathbf{r}</m> represents the first displacement.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lmmurbh0">
                    <p xml:id="auto_5rt4rdjn">
                        <m>\mathbf{QN} = \mathbf{s}</m> represents the second displacement.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_w6gwagk6">
            Therefore, <m> \mathbf{PN} = \mathbf{r} + \mathbf{s}</m>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="adding-vectors-120">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="45%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                        % Define points
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (3,2);
                        \coordinate (N) at (5,0);

                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) node[midway, above] {\small $r$};
                        \draw[thick] (Q) -- (N) node[midway, right] {\small $s$};
                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (N) node[midway, below] {\small $r+s$};

                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=0.8]}] (P) -- (1.5,1);
                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=0.8]}] (Q) -- (4.2,0.8);
                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=0.8]}] (P) -- (2.5,0);

                        \node[left] at (0,0) {P};
                        \node[above] at (3,2) {Q};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {N};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p xml:id="auto_qrt0hg73">
            We can also re-arrange the two vectors and add 
            them together as shown in <xref ref="adding-vectors-1200"/> below.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="adding-vectors-1200">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="45%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                        % Define points
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (3,2);
                        \coordinate (N) at (5,0);
                        \coordinate (M) at (3,-2);

                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) node[midway, above] {\small $r$};
                        \draw[thick] (Q) -- (N) node[midway, right] {\small $s$};
                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (N) node[midway, above] {\small $r+s$};
                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (N) node[midway, below] {\small $s+r$};

                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (M) node[midway, below] {\small $s$};
                        \draw[thick] (M) -- (N) node[midway, right] {\small $r$};


                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=1]}] (P) -- (1.5,1);
                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=1]}] (Q) -- (4.2,0.8);
                        %\draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=1]}] (P) -- (2.5,0);

                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=1]}] (P) -- (1.5,-1);
                        \draw[thick,-{Latex[scale=1]}] (N) -- (4,-1);

                        \node[left] at (0,0) {P};
                        \node[above] at (3,2) {Q};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {N};
                        \node[below] at (3,-2) {M};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </insight>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_90kj0nzu">
            After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries using the Key Takeaway above.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_54kvll4x">
            <alert>Key Concepts to Emphasise:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8g5hmb9q">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_xit08618"><p xml:id="auto_p71it8dq"><alert>Tip-to-tail method:</alert> Place the tail of the second vector at the tip of the first. The resultant goes from the starting tail to the final tip.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6ev18j6j"><p xml:id="auto_3hvvex9p"><alert>Component addition:</alert> Add <m>x</m>-components together and <m>y</m>-components together separately.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6d0rzfso"><p xml:id="auto_jtsjbz6b">Vector addition is commutative: <m>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{a}</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_smskfm18"><p xml:id="auto_golpqjoz">Vector addition is associative: <m>(\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}) + \mathbf{c} = \mathbf{a} + (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c})</m>.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_49ylysoq">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o0u9k3ed">
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Vectors are added tail-to-tail</cell>
                    <cell>No — use tip-to-tail (head-to-tail) method</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>The resultant goes from tip to tip</cell>
                    <cell>No — it goes from the starting tail to the final tip</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Add all components together as one number</cell>
                    <cell>No — add <m>x</m>-components and <m>y</m>-components separately</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (15 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_5ew9c2t2">
            Walk students through the worked example below. Emphasise the sequential path from one point to another and combining vectors along that path.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0k5hhib5">
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zx1pu0os">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_vrnso10i"><p xml:id="auto_ww2qk1pv"><q>What path do we follow from <m>A</m> to <m>D</m>?</q> (Through <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>.)</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gibkts54"><p xml:id="auto_fr7c9q80"><q>How do we express <m>\overrightarrow{AD}</m> using the vectors along the path?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n35ny244"><p xml:id="auto_wvtrhfmj">Connect graphical and algebraic methods as two ways to solve the same problem.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_9m2vj9xl">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_3t0pueyz">
                In <xref ref="example-vector-addition"/> below, find vector <m>\mathbf{AD}</m> in terms of <m>\mathbf{a}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b}</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="example-vector-addition">
                <caption></caption>
                <image width="40%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \coordinate (A) at (2,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (4,5);
                        \coordinate (C) at (8,6);
                        \coordinate (D) at (9,3);
                        
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D);
                        
                        \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[above] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above] at (C) {C};
                        \node[right] at (D) {D};
                        
                        \draw[-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (A) -- (3,3);
                        \draw[-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (B) -- (6,5.5);
                        \draw[-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (C) -- (8.5,4.5);
                        
                        % \node[midway above] (A) -- (B) {a};
                        % \node[midway above] (B) -- (C) {b};
                        % \node[midway above] (C) -- (D) {c};
                        
                        \path (A) -- (B) node[midway, left] {$\mathbf{a}$};
                        \path (B) -- (C) node[midway, above] {$\mathbf{b}$};
                        \path (C) -- (D) node[midway, right] {$\mathbf{c}$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_cze0irgo">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \overrightarrow{AD}  \amp = \overrightarrow{AB} + \overrightarrow{BC} + \overrightarrow{CD}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5y6jcsar">
                Thus, <m>\overrightarrow{AD} = \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qa73f50n">
            <alert>Exit Ticket</alert> — Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_moeade1c">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_eighy2d2"><p xml:id="auto_b9mgnyxx">On graph paper, draw vectors <m>\mathbf{a} = \binom{3}{1}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \binom{2}{4}</m>. Add them graphically using the tip-to-tail method and state the resultant vector.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1rn5mqwo"><p xml:id="auto_52cjxclz">In triangle <m>ABC</m>, <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = \mathbf{p}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{BC} = \mathbf{q}</m>. Express <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m> in terms of <m>\mathbf{p}</m> and <m>\mathbf{q}</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_02zni6sy"><p xml:id="auto_xetb2gnz">Given <m>\mathbf{x} = 3\mathbf{m} - \mathbf{n}</m>, express <m>3\mathbf{x}</m> in terms of <m>\mathbf{m}</m> and <m>\mathbf{n}</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_iioci51i">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cgkrvt3x">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_8rpjzxs3"><p xml:id="auto_grxznk55">Resultant: <m>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} = \binom{5}{5}</m>. Draw <m>\mathbf{a}</m> from origin to <m>(3,1)</m>, then <m>\mathbf{b}</m> from <m>(3,1)</m> to <m>(5,5)</m>. Resultant goes from origin to <m>(5,5)</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_k1lujnde"><p xml:id="auto_jhf0peat"><m>\overrightarrow{AC} = \mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q}</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qnqvpehw"><p xml:id="auto_x3bdw1et"><m>3\mathbf{x} = 3(3\mathbf{m} - \mathbf{n}) = 9\mathbf{m} - 3\mathbf{n}</m></p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-addition-of-vectors">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_mta5a7qu">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_2d01m7q4">
                    <m>PQNM</m> is a square with vectors
                    <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m> and <m>\mathbf{PM}</m> given 
                    as <m>\mathbf{a} \text{ and } \mathbf{b}</m> respectively,
                    as shown in <xref ref="exercise-addition-vectors-1"/> . Express the <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> and 
                    <m>\mathbf{MQ}</m> vectors in terms of <m>\mathbf{a}</m> and 
                    <m>\mathbf{b}</m>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="exercise-addition-vectors-1">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image width="30%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            
                                % Define points
                                \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (Q) at (5,0);
                                \coordinate (N) at (5,5);
                                \coordinate (M) at (0,5);

                                %square
                                \draw[very thick] (P) -- (Q);
                                \draw[very thick] (Q) -- (N);
                                \draw[very thick] (N) -- (M);
                                \draw[very thick] (M) -- (P);
                                
                                %diagonals
                                
                                \draw[dashed] (M) -- (Q);
                                \draw[dashed] (P) -- (N);
                                
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[draw=black,size=.4](M,P,Q);
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[draw=black,size=.4](P,Q,N);
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[draw=black,size=.4](Q,N,M);
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[draw=black,size=.4](N,M,P);
                                
                                %arrows
                                \draw[-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (P) -- (0,2.5);
                                \draw[-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (P) -- (2.5,0);
                                
                                \node[below] at (P) {P};
                                \node[below] at (Q) {Q};
                                \node[above] at (N) {N};
                                \node[above] at (M) {M};

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_3st2kb15">
                    <m>\mathbf{PN} = \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_b4htlrnh">
                    <m>\mathbf{MQ} = \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}</m> or <m>-\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{a}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_mvgopmga">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_sjnrdd4y">
                    Use <xref ref="exercise-addition-of-vectors-1-1"/> to answer the questions below:
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="exercise-addition-of-vectors-1-1">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw the grid
                            \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (0,0) grid (15,15);
                            \draw[step=1cm,black!40,thick] (0,0) grid (15,15);

                            % Draw the vectors (approximate based on the image)
                            \draw[thick] (0,13) -- (2,14) node[midway, above] {\large $e$};
                            \draw[thick] (10,1) -- (12,2) node[midway, above] {\large $d$};
                            \draw[thick] (5,5) -- (9,8) node[midway, above] {\large $b$};
                            \draw[thick] (3,11) -- (7,14) node[midway, above] {\large$f$};
                            \draw[thick] (1,1) -- (4,3) node[midway, above] {\large $g$};
                            \draw[thick] (12,12) -- (15,14) node[midway, above] {\large $h$};

                            %Draw the vectors
                            \draw[-{Latex[scale=2]}] (0,13) -- (1,13.5);
                            \draw[-{Latex[scale=2]}] (10,1) -- (11,1.5);
                            \draw[-{Latex[scale=2]}] (3,11) -- (5,12.5);
                            \draw[-{Latex[scale=2]}]  (9,8) -- (7,6.5);
                            \draw[-{Latex[scale=2]}]  (4,3) -- (2.5,2);
                            \draw[-{Latex[scale=2]}]  (15,14) --  (13.5,13);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p xml:id="auto_1dslxf0f">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_niofykca" marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_b10udfok">
                            <p xml:id="auto_effschol">
                                List pairs of equal vectors.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_58408u0z">
                            <p xml:id="auto_y6alikt0">
                                Name pairs of vectors with equal magnitude but opposite directions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <!-- <li xml:id="auto_w7gb014n">
                            <p xml:id="auto_sl5k3zq1">
                                illustrate the sums of the following vectors graphically:
                                <ol xml:id="auto_tbqjr5zr" marker="(i)" cols="2">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_ogr7iz68">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_kyjifgam">
                                            <m>\mathbf{e} + \mathbf{d}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_qd6p3mpw">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_y30q1z5y">
                                            <m>\mathbf{f} + \mathbf{g}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_ybawg4v9">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_coxeuk7v">
                                            <m>\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{d}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_pz6jfa0j">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_cd7wh93g">
                                            <m>\mathbf{g} + \mathbf{h}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li> -->
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_6z3ibuc2">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_7qz2cfm0">
                            <p xml:id="auto_btjtsh3c">
                                Pairs of equal vectors
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_s0rw1u0r">
                                <ul>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_3xxgxw7a">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_px64d230">
                                            <m>\mathbf{e}</m> and <m>\mathbf{d}</m> (both are <m>2</m> units right, <m>1</m> unit up).
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_s582awrx">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_gliztfbh">
                                            <m>\mathbf{g}</m> and <m>\mathbf{h}</m> (both are <m>3</m> units right, <m>2</m> units up).
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_8d6kfruy">
                            <p xml:id="auto_s4ekqbda">
                                Equal magnitude, opposite direction
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_2do7hccd">
                                <ul>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_twe3z7at">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_16m39mc6">
                                            <m>\mathbf{f} </m> and <m>\mathbf{b}</m> both have same magnitude but different directions.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_x41yaqft">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_q7ivy5jn">
                    Given the vectors <m>\mathbf{a} = \binom{2}{3}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \binom{4}{-1}</m>, 
                    find <m>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}</m> and illustrate the solution graphically.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_iembtu8r">
                    <m>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} = \binom{6}{2}</m>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="addition-of-column-vectors">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Draw fine grid
                                \draw[gray!20, very thin, step=0.5] (-1,-1) grid (7,5);
                                % Draw main grid
                                \draw[gray!50, thin, step=1] (-1,-1) grid (7,5);

                                % Draw axes
                                \draw[thick,-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (7,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,-0.5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};

                                % Axis labels
                                \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6} \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node[below] {\small \x};
                                \foreach \y in {1,2,3,4} \draw (0.1,\y) -- (-0.1,\y) node[left] {\small \y};
                                \node[below left] at (0,0) {0};

                                % Coordinates based on the text
                                \coordinate (Origin) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (A) at (2,3);
                                \coordinate (B_End) at (6,2);

                                % Vector a: (0,0) to (2,3)
                                \draw[blue, thick, -{Latex[length=3mm]}] (Origin) -- (A) 
                                    node[midway, left] {$\mathbf{a}$};

                                % Vector b: (2,3) to (6,2) 
                                % (Note: This is moving 4 units right and 1 unit down)
                                \draw[red, thick, -{Latex[length=3mm]}] (A) -- (B_End) 
                                    node[midway, above right] {$\mathbf{b}$};

                                % Resultant Vector: (0,0) to (6,2)
                                \draw[purple, ultra thick, -{Latex[length=3mm]}] (Origin) -- (B_End) 
                                    node[midway, below] {$\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}$};

                                % Label key points
                                \fill (Origin) circle (2pt) node[below left] {(0,0)};
                                \fill (A) circle (2pt) node[above] {(2,3)};
                                \fill (B_End) circle (2pt) node[right] {(6,2)};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_5jv1zt70">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sc3bile0">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_zjhaz1fl"><p xml:id="auto_vthb9ve0">Provide pre-drawn axes on graph paper.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zdhdsfzn"><p xml:id="auto_flro87jb">Use colour coding: first vector in blue, second in red, resultant in green.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0g1zv5n8"><p xml:id="auto_0jcg7im6">Start with simple horizontal and vertical vectors before diagonal ones.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rnerm50b"><p xml:id="auto_d95vsgc2">Provide step-by-step templates for algebraic addition.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yr2b0uej"><p xml:id="auto_4xev0xs1">Use physical arrows or string to demonstrate the tip-to-tail method.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bjiej334">
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_531utfx5">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_8kept4ps"><p xml:id="auto_7web6o25">Encourage students to verify graphical answers with algebraic methods.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qfrrpd24"><p xml:id="auto_haz2xn0c">Provide mixed practice combining two and three vectors.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_c47bpazt"><p xml:id="auto_vhosganr">Challenge students to express diagonals of shapes in terms of side vectors.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_mgqkntdh">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_d2eutdx2">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_tuuqbjri"><p xml:id="auto_z26nzff2">Introduce vector subtraction (adding negative vectors).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_64odwu82"><p xml:id="auto_z4ya6gbw">Explore three-dimensional vector addition.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_htkem6vm"><p xml:id="auto_8ggyfck2">Connect to the parallelogram law of vector addition.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tv5y64nc"><p xml:id="auto_1y3kf3ix">Investigate the triangle inequality: <m>|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}| \leq |\mathbf{a}| + |\mathbf{b}|</m>.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_h6f87p8f">
            <alert>Extension Activity: Navigation Challenge</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2l99ttty">
            Design a journey with three legs (e.g., walk 5 km east, then 3 km north, then 4 km west). Represent each leg as a vector, add them to find the resultant displacement, and compare total distance travelled with displacement.
        </p>
    </axiom>
